# LAU Soft Skills Event Website — Non-Technical Requirements (ONLINE VERSION)

> **Project type:** Capstone-level digital event platform  
> **Event:** LAU Soft Skills Event (online via Zoom / Teams / Webex)  
> **Primary goal:** Deliver a **seamless online event experience** where:
>
> - attendees can follow the event easily
> - judges can evaluate efficiently and reliably
> - participants are showcased professionally
>
> **Priority shift:**  
> 🔴 Judge grading system + usability  
> 🟡 Clean attendee experience  
> 🟢 Memorability through UI/UX (without unnecessary complexity)

---

## 1) Vision & Product Definition

### 1.1 What this platform is now

The website becomes the **central control hub** of the online event.
Instead of enhancing a physical event, it now:

- replaces confusion in Zoom/Teams chats
- organizes all content in one place
- acts as the **official interface for judging, viewing, and interaction**

### 1.2 Core metaphor (refined): “Spotlight”

Still keep the metaphor, but adapt it to online:

- Each speaker/team is “in the spotlight”
- The site guides users between “who’s live now” and “who’s next”
- The experience feels structured and professional, not chaotic like typical online events

---

## 2) Success Definition (Online Context)

The platform is successful if:

- Judges say: “grading was easy and smooth”
- Attendees say: “I always knew where to go”
- No one asks: “Where is the link?” or “What’s happening now?”
- The site feels more organized than the Zoom/Webex interface

### Measurable outcomes:

- Judges complete all evaluations without issues
- Minimal confusion messages during the event
- High participation in People’s Choice voting
- Positive feedback on clarity and professionalism

---

## 3) Target Users & Needs

### 3.1 Judges (MOST IMPORTANT)

**Primary user group**
Needs:

- Clear login
- Access to all teams/speakers
- Structured rubric-based evaluation
- Ability to:
  - enter scores
  - edit scores
  - submit final results
- Zero risk of losing progress

---

### 3.2 Attendees (students, viewers)

Needs:

- Know what’s happening now
- Easily join the correct Zoom/Teams/Webex link
- Browse speakers and projects
- Vote for People’s Choice
- Leave comments/feedback

---

### 3.3 Participants (teams/speakers)

Needs:

- Professional representation (spotlight pages)
- Their work clearly displayed
- Feedback visibility (comments)

---

## 4) Event Flow (Online Adaptation)

### 4.1 Before the event

- Users explore:
  - speakers
  - projects
  - event structure
- Optional: pre-uploaded pitch videos

---

### 4.2 During the event (CRITICAL)

The website becomes the **navigation system for the event**
Users rely on it for:

- “Join session” buttons (Zoom/Webex links)
- “Now Playing”
- “Up Next”
- Voting
- Viewing participants

---

### 4.3 After the event

- Archive:
  - winners
  - projects
  - speakers
  - pitch videos
- Comments remain visible

---

## 5) Core Features (Public Experience)

---

### 5.1 Live Navigation Hub (MOST IMPORTANT PAGE)

**Purpose:** Replace confusion in online meetings.
This is the first thing users should open.

#### Requirements:

- **Now Playing**
  - current segment (TED / Pitch / Expo)
  - speaker/team name
  - **JOIN BUTTON (Zoom/Webex link)**
- **Up Next**
  - next speaker/team
  - optional countdown
- Clear actions:
  - View speakers
  - View projects
  - Vote
  - Switch language

#### UX rules:

- One-glance understanding
- No clutter
- Large buttons (especially “Join Session”)

---

### 5.2 Spotlight Pages (Speakers + Projects)

**Purpose:** Make participants look professional and organized.
Each page includes:

- Photo / team image
- Name + title
- Bio / project description
- Tags (category)
- Pitch video (if available or placeholder)
- Actions:
  - Vote
  - Comment
  - (Optional) Join session if live

#### UX requirements:

- Clean layout
- Mobile-first
- Consistent across all pages

---

### 5.3 Project Browsing (List instead of Map)

Since event is online:

- Replace physical map with:
  - **List view**
  - Filter by category
  - Search
    Optional:
- Highlight “Currently Presenting”

---

### 5.4 People’s Choice Voting

**Purpose:** Keep audience engaged

#### Requirements:

- Simple voting flow:
  1. Browse projects
  2. Click vote
  3. Confirmation
- Rate limiting:
  - Prevent spam without login
  - Keep it frictionless

#### UX:

- No complicated steps
- Clear feedback after voting

---

### 5.5 Comments / Feedback System

**Purpose:** Replace physical feedback and add interaction

#### Requirements:

- Available on:
  - pitch pages
  - project pages
- Encourage meaningful comments:
  - “What did you like?”
  - “One suggestion”
- Clean display (not messy threads)

#### Safety:

- Light moderation or reporting system

---

## 6) Core Features (Judge System — CRITICAL)

---

### 6.1 Judge Login

Requirements:

- Simple login (email/password or code)
- Persistent session (don’t log them out mid-event)
- Clear “Judge Mode” indicator

---

### 6.2 Judge Dashboard

**Purpose:** Central grading interface

#### Requirements:

- List of all teams/projects
- Status indicators:
  - Not graded
  - In progress
  - Submitted

---

### 6.3 Grading Interface (MOST IMPORTANT FEATURE)

**Purpose:** Replace paper rubric

#### Requirements:

- For each project:
  - Show team info
  - Show rubric fields (to be added later)
- Judges can:
  - enter scores
  - edit scores
  - save progress
  - submit final evaluation

#### UX rules:

- Extremely clear layout
- No distractions
- Fast input (no lag)
- Large inputs, easy navigation

---

### 6.4 Reliability Requirements

- **No data loss**
- Auto-save (recommended)
- Clear “Saved” indicator
- Confirmation on submission

---

## 7) Information Architecture

### Main navigation:

- Home
- Live / Join
- Program
- Speakers
- Projects
- Vote
- Judge Portal

---

### UX rule:

Users must reach key actions in **≤ 2 clicks**:

- Join session
- Vote
- View projects

---

## 8) Bilingual Experience (English + Arabic)

Requirements:

- Language toggle always visible
- Arabic supports RTL properly
- No layout breaking when switching
- Users stay on same page when switching language

---

## 9) UI/UX Quality (Capstone Focus)

---

### 9.1 Simplicity first

- No unnecessary features
- Every element must have a purpose

---

### 9.2 Visual hierarchy

Every screen must answer:

1. What is happening?
2. What can I do?
3. What should I do next?

---

### 9.3 Motion design (subtle)

- Smooth transitions
- No heavy animations
- Used to guide attention only

---

### 9.4 Mobile-first

- Most users will use phones
- Large buttons
- Minimal scrolling
- Fast loading

---

### 9.5 Accessibility

- Readable text
- Good contrast
- Keyboard support
- RTL Arabic usability

---

## 10) Content Strategy

---

### 10.1 Placeholder handling

Since content arrives late:

- Use clean placeholders
- “Coming soon” labels
- Consistent structure

---

### 10.2 Tone

- Professional
- Clear
- Minimal
  Examples:
- “Join session”
- “Now presenting”
- “Vote for People’s Choice”
- “Leave feedback”

---

## 11) Performance & Reliability

---

### Requirements:

- Fast loading (especially mobile)
- Stable during peak usage (50–100 users)
- No broken links (especially meeting links)

---

### Critical:

- Join buttons must always work
- Judge system must never crash

---

## 12) Scope Control

---

### MVP (must have)

- Live navigation hub with join links
- Speakers + projects pages
- People’s Choice voting
- Judge login + grading system
- Bilingual support

---

### Capstone polish

